                        <note rend="inline" type="source"><persName corresp="#p_MS1">Mikołajczyk</persName> Papers</note>
                        <head>No. 1392<lb/><hi rend="italic">Diary Entry by the Polish Deputy Prime
                                Minister</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MS1"><hi rend="italic">Mikołajczyk</hi></persName>)<note n="1" xml:id="d1392fn1">Cf.
                                    <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_480">p.
                                480</ref>.</note></head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Translation]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Babelsberg</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-07-30">July 30, 1945</date>.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>A Polish-American conference was held at the headquarters of the Polish
                                Delegation<note n="2" xml:id="d1392fn2">At 10 Domgasse, Babelsberg.
                                See <persName corresp="#p_LAB1">Lane</persName>, <hi rend="italic">I
                                    Saw Poland Betrayed</hi>, p. 130.</note> concerning a
                            transaction with regard to 2,500 tons of coal to be delivered to the
                            American occupation sector in Berlin. The transaction was based on a
                            payment in dollars, but the Polish side retained the right to accept oil
                            or gasoline in payment for the supply of coal. The Americans would
                            provide railroad freight cars for the coal and would send them to the
                            place of loading.</p>
